-- Japan, China, India, Indonesia, South Korea: Asian Bonds, Currency Preview
-- Anil Varma
-- 2010-07-26T22:29:33Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-07-26/japan-china-india-indonesia-south-korea-asian-bonds-currency-preview.html

          
          
             The following events and economic
reports may influence trading in Asia’s local bonds and
currencies today. Bond yields and exchange rates are from the
previous trading session unless stated otherwise.  
 Japan: Chief Cabinet Secretary  Yoshito Sengoku  and Finance
Minister  Yoshihiko Noda  will hold media briefings after a
cabinet meeting in the morning. Sengoku will have another press
briefing at 4 p.m. in Tokyo.  
 The Bank of Japan will release at 8:50 a.m. its report on
corporate service prices for June. The prices which Japanese
companies pay for services such as transportation and
advertisements fell 0.9 percent in June from a year earlier,
according to a Bloomberg News survey of economists.  
 The Ministry of Finance will announce at 10:30 a.m. the
amount of 10-year government bonds it plans to sell on Aug. 3.  
 The yield on the 1.1 percent government bond due June 2020
was 1.06 percent, according to Japan Bond Trading Co., the
nation’s largest interdealer debt broker.  
 The yen traded at 87 per dollar at 7:21 a.m. in Tokyo.  
 China: The finance ministry plans to sell as much as 28
billion yuan ($4.1 billion) of 30-year debt. Separately, the
Export-Import Bank of China will offer 10 billion yuan of three-
year bonds.  
 The yield on the 2.53 percent note due in June 2015 was
2.60 percent. The yuan was at 6.7795 per dollar.  
 India: The Reserve Bank of India will probably increase its
reverse repurchase rate by a quarter-point to 4.25 percent at a
meeting today, all 20 forecasts in a Bloomberg News survey
showed. It will raise the repurchase rate to 5.75 percent from
5.5 percent, according to all but one analyst, who expects it to
be kept unchanged.  
 The yield on the 7.80 percent bond due May 2020 was 7.67
percent. The rupee was at 47.05.  
 Indonesia: The government will offer Islamic bonds maturing
in five, seven, 10, 15 and 20 years. It also plans to sell
retail bonds.  
 The yield on the 11 percent bond due November 2020 was at
8.24 percent, according to Inter Dealer Market Association. The
rupiah was at 9,030.  
 Philippines: The National Statistics Office will release
trade data for May. The nation’s trade deficit widened to $846
million in April from $362 million in March.  
 The yield on the 7.75 percent debt due February 2020 was
7.63 percent, according to Philippine Dealing & Exchange Corp.
The peso was at 46.120  
 South Korea: South Korea’s consumer confidence held at a
five-month high in July, the Bank of Korea said. The sentiment
index was 112, unchanged from June and the highest level since
January, the Bank of Korea said in an e-mailed statement in
Seoul today. A number exceeding 100 indicates optimists
outnumber pessimists.  
 The yield on the 4.50 percent bond due in March 2015 was
4.43 percent. The won was at 1,191.30.  
 Thailand: The central bank will auction 20 billion baht
($621 million) of 28-day bills and 15 billion baht each of 91-
day and 182-day notes.  
 The yield on the 3.875 percent bond maturing in June 2019
was 3.41 percent. The baht was at 32.21.  
